# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ubuntu-linux
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] APT is a collection of tools distributed in a package named *apt*.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] A significant part of APT is defined in a C++ library of functions; APT also includes command-line programs for dealing with packages, which use the library.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] Three such programs are `apt`, `apt-get` and `apt-cache`.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] They are commonly used in examples because they are simple and ubiquitous.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] The *apt* package is of "*important*" priority in all current Debian releases, and is therefore included in a default Debian installation.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] APT can be considered a front end to `dpkg`, friendlier than the older `dselect` front end.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] While `dpkg` performs actions on individual packages, APT manages relations (especially dependencies) between them, as well as sourcing and management of higher-level versioning decisions such as release tracking and Upgrade Suppression.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] APT is often hailed as one of Debian's best features, which Debian developers attribute to the strict quality controls in Debian's policy.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] A major feature of APT is the way it calls `dpkg` –it performs topological sorting of the list of packages to be installed or removed and calls `dpkg` in the best possible sequence.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] In some cases, it utilizes the `--force` options of `dpkg`.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] However, it only does this when it is unable to calculate how to avoid the reason `dpkg` requires the action to be forced.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] The user indicates one or more packages to be installed.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] Each package name is phrased as just the name portion of the package, not a fully qualified filename (for instance, in a Debian system, `libc6` would be the argument provided, not `libc6_1.9.6-2.deb`).
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] Notably, APT automatically gets and installs packages upon which the indicated package depends (if necessary).
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] This was an original distinguishing characteristic of APT-based package management systems, as it avoided installation failure due to missing dependencies, a type of dependency hell.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] Another distinction is the retrieval of packages from remote repositories.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] APT uses a location configuration file (`/etc/apt/sources.list`) to locate the desired packages, which might be available on the network or a removable storage medium, for example, and retrieve them, and also obtain information about available (but not installed) packages.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] APT provides other command options to override decisions made by apt-get's conflict resolution system.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] One option is to force a particular version of a package.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] This can downgrade a package and render dependent software inoperable, so the user must be careful.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] Finally, the `apt_preferences` mechanism allows the user to create an alternative installation policy for individual packages.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] The user can specify packages using a POSIX regular expression.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] APT searches its cached list of packages and lists the dependencies that must be installed or updated.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] APT retrieves, configures and installs the dependencies automatically.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] Triggers are the treatment of deferred actions.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] `/etc/apt` contains the APT configuration folders and files.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] `apt-config` is the APT Configuration Query program.
[src:ubuntu-linux/apt-software] `apt-config dump` shows the configuration.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] Canonical Ltd. has created and continues to back several projects.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] Principally these are free and open-source software (FOSS) or tools designed to improve collaboration between free software developers and contributors.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] Some projects require a Contributor License Agreement to be signed.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] In 2007, Canonical launched an International online shop selling support services and Ubuntu-branded goods; later in 2008 it expanded that with a United States-specific shop designed to reduce shipment times.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] At the same time, the word *Ubuntu* was trademarked in connection with clothing and accessories.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] In a *Guardian* interview in May 2008, Shuttleworth said that Canonical's business model was service provision and that Canonical was not yet close to profitability.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] Canonical stated that it would wait three to five years to become profitable.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] Shuttleworth regarded Canonical as positioning itself as demand for services related to free software rose.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] This strategy has been compared to Red Hat's business strategies in the 1990s.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] In an early-2009 *New York Times* article, Shuttleworth said that Canonical's revenue was "creeping" towards US$30 million, the company's break-even point.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] Canonical achieved a small operating profit of $281,000 in 2009, but until 2017 struggled to maintain financial solvency and took a major financial hit from the development of Unity and Ubuntu Touch, leading to an operating loss of $21.6 million for the fiscal year 2013.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] The company reported an operating profit of $2 million in 2017 after shutting down the Unity development team and laying off nearly 200 employees.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] The company now plans to focus on its server and professional support products and services, which have proved to be most profitable.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] Through this, Canonical plans to maintain solvency and achieve long-term profitability.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] In 2022, Canonical UK Limited (a subsidiary of the group) made a profit of £0.52m on revenues of £14.31m.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] Canonical reported a revenue of $175M in 2021.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] In 2023, the company reported a revenue of $251M.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] The head office is in London on the 5th Floor of 3 More London Riverside, More London.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] Previous office locations include the 5th Floor of the Blue Fin Building, Southwark Street, and the 27th floor of Millbank Tower.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] In the summer of 2006, Canonical opened an office in Montreal to house its global support and services operation.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] Taipei 101 is also home to a Canonical office.
[src:ubuntu-linux/canonical-company] There was formerly an OEM team in Lexington, Massachusetts, United States.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME is developed by the GNOME Project, which is composed of both volunteers and paid contributors, the largest corporate contributor being Red Hat.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] It is an international project that aims to develop frameworks for software development, to program end-user applications based on these frameworks, and to coordinate efforts for the internationalization, localization, and accessibility of that software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] In 2023 and 2024, GNOME received €1,000,000 from Germany's Sovereign Tech Fund.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Since GNOME 2, productivity has been a key focus for GNOME.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] To meet this end, the GNOME Human Interface Guidelines (HIG) were created.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] All GNOME programs share a coherent style of interfaces but are not limited to the employment of the same GUI widgets.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Rather, the design of the GNOME's interface is guided by concepts described in the HIG, itself relying on insights from cognitive ergonomics.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Following the HIG, developers can create high-quality, consistent, and usable GUI programs, as it addresses everything from interface design to the recommended pixel-based layout of widgets.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] However, critics have complained about GNOME ignoring traditional user interface conventions, and the wasting of screen real estate.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] During the GNOME 2 rewrite, many settings deemed of little value to the majority of users were removed.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME aims to make and keep the desktop environment physically and cognitively ergonomic for people with disabilities.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The GNOME Human Interface Guidelines try to take this into account as far as possible but specific issues are solved by special software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME addresses computer accessibility issues by using the Accessibility Toolkit (ATK) application programming interface, which allows enhancing user experience by using special input methods and speech synthesis and speech recognition software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Particular utilities are registered with ATK using Assistive Technology Service Provider Interface (AT-SPI), and become globally used throughout the desktop.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Several assistive technology providers, including Orca screen reader and Dasher input method, were developed specifically for use with GNOME.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The internationalization and localization of GNOME software relies on locale, and supports 197 languages with varying levels of completion, with some not being translated at all.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME Shell is the main graphical shell of GNOME.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] It features a top bar holding (from left to right) an Overview button, a clock and an integrated system status menu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The application menu displays the name of the application in focus and provides access to functions such as accessing the application's preferences, closing the application, or creating a new application window.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The status menu holds various system status indicators, shortcuts to system settings, and session actions including logging out, switching users, locking the screen, and suspending the computer.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Clicking on the Activities button, moving the mouse to the top-left hot corner or pressing the Super key brings up the Overview.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The Overview gives users an overview of current activities and provides a way to switch between windows and workspaces and to launch applications.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The Dash on the bottom houses shortcuts to favorite applications, currently open windows, and an application picker button to show a list of all installed applications.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] A search bar appears at the top and a workspace list for viewing and switching between workspaces is directly above it.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Notifications appear from the top of the shell.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME Classic also adds the minimize and maximize buttons to window headers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] There are a large number of GTK-based programs written by various authors.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Since the release of GNOME 3.0, GNOME Project concentrates on developing a set of programs that accounts for the GNOME Core Applications.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The commonalities of the GNOME Core Applications are the adherence to the current GNOME Human Interface Guidelines (HIG) as well as the tight integration with underlying GNOME layers like e.g.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GVfs (GNOME virtual filesystem) and also with one another e.g.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GOA (gnome-online-accounts) settings and GNOME Files with Google Drive and GNOME Photos with Google Photos.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Some programs are simply existing programs with a new name and revamped user interface, while others have been written from scratch.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The GNOME project provides a suite of software development tools to facilitate the creation of GNOME software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] These tools are designed to streamline the development process for the GNOME ecosystem.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] These tools collectively provide a comprehensive development environment for creating software that aligns with the GNOME desktop and its design principles.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME Circle is a collection of applications which have been built to extend the GNOME platform, utilize GNOME technologies, and follow the GNOME human interface guidelines.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME was started on 15 August 1997 by Miguel de Icaza and Federico Mena as a free software project to develop a desktop environment and applications for it.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] It was founded in part because the K Desktop Environment, which was growing in popularity, relied on the Qt widget toolkit which used a proprietary software license until version 2.0 (June 1999).
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] In place of Qt, GTK (formerly called GIMP Toolkit) was chosen as the base of GNOME.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GTK is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL), a free software license that allows software linking to it to use a much wider set of licenses, including proprietary software licenses.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME itself is licensed under the LGPL for its libraries and the GNU General Public License (GPL) for its applications.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME was formerly a part of the GNU Project, but that is no longer the case.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] In 2021, GNOME Executive Director Neil McGovern publicly tweeted that GNOME was not a GNU project and that he had been asking GNU to remove GNOME from their list of packages since 2019.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] In 2021, GNOME was removed from the list.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME proceeded to remove mentions of any link to GNU from their code and documentation.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The name "GNOME" was initially an acronym for *GNU Network Object Model Environment*, referring to the original intention of creating a distributed object framework similar to Microsoft's OLE, but the acronym was eventually dropped because it no longer reflected the vision of the GNOME project.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The California startup Eazel developed the Nautilus file manager from 1999 to 2001.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] De Icaza and Nat Friedman founded Helix Code (later Ximian) in 1999 in Massachusetts; this company developed GNOME's infrastructure and applications and was purchased by Novell in 2003.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] During the transition to GNOME 2 and shortly thereafter, there were brief talks about creating a *GNOME Office* suite.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] On 15 September 2003 GNOME-Office 1.0, consisting of AbiWord 2.0, GNOME-DB 1.0, and Gnumeric 1.2.0, was released.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Although some release planning for GNOME Office 1.2 was happening on the gnome-office mailing list, and Gnumeric 1.4 was announced as a part of it, the 1.2 release of the suite itself never materialized.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] As of 4 May 2014, the GNOME wiki only mentions "GNOME/GTK applications that are useful in an office environment".
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 2 was released in June 2002 and was very similar to a conventional desktop interface, featuring a simple desktop in which users could interact with virtual objects such as windows, icons, and files.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 2 started out with Sawfish as its default window manager, but later switched to Metacity in GNOME 2.2.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The handling of windows, applications, and files in GNOME 2 is similar to that of contemporary desktop operating systems.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] However, these features can be moved to almost any position or orientation the user desires, replaced with other functions, or removed altogether.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] As of 2009, GNOME 2 was the default desktop for OpenSolaris.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] In 2008, an increasing discontent among the community and developers about the lack of project direction and technical progress prompted the announcement of GNOME 3.0.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Originally, the plan was to make only incremental changes and avoid disruption for users.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] This changed when efforts led to the creation of the GNOME Shell.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 3 brought many enhancements to core software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Many GNOME Core Applications also went through redesigns to provide a better user experience.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Mutter replaced Metacity as the default window manager, and Adwaita replaced Clearlooks as the default theme.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The release of GNOME 3 caused considerable controversy in the GNU and Linux communities.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Aiming to provide an easy-to-use and uncluttered user experience has led to some criticized design decisions, like the removal of *minimize* and *maximize* buttons, the simplification of configuration options, and visual cues that could lead to confusion.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Among those critical of the early releases of GNOME 3 is Linus Torvalds, the creator of the Linux kernel.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Torvalds abandoned GNOME for a while after the release of GNOME 3.0, saying, "The developers have apparently decided that it's 'too complicated' to actually do real work on your desktop, and have decided to make it really annoying to do".
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Over time, critical reception has grown more positive.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] In 2013, Torvalds resumed using GNOME, noting that "they have extensions now that are still much too hard to find; but with extensions you can make your desktop look almost as good as it used to look two years ago".
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Debian, a Linux distribution that had historically used GNOME 2, switched to Xfce when GNOME 3 was released, but re-adopted GNOME 3 in time for the release of Debian 8 "Jessie".
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Ubuntu switched from Unity to GNOME 3 with several extensions to resemble Unity, such as a persistent left application panel instead of a hidden dock and re-enabling desktop icons, with Ubuntu 17.10 Artful Aardvark in 2017.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] This release also saw the Ubuntu GNOME edition merge with the mainline release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] However, Ubuntu Unity was then released, keeping the Unity desktop and continuing to update it.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] It immediately follows version 3, but adopts a new versioning scheme and a schedule of future major releases on a fixed six-month cycle (see Release Cycle).
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] With this quicker release cadence, major releases became somewhat leaner, because full rewrites of major packages were not occurring as often as they were in the jumps between GNOME 1.0, 2.0, and 3.0 versions.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 40 organizes the activities overview in a horizontal fashion, instead of using a vertical design like its predecessors.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The release also brings new touchpad gestures.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 42 was released on 23 March 2022 and introduced the option to screen record and switch light/dark themes using a new GTK API called Libadwaita.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Several default apps were replaced with more modern versions such as Text Editor instead of Gedit and Console instead of Terminal.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 43 (Guadalajara) was released on 21 September 2022 and introduced a new quick settings menu, a GNOME Files update to GTK4, and a new 'Device Security' panel in settings, among many other changes.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME Web was updated, bringing in support for web apps and experimental Firefox and Chrome extension support.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 44 (Kuala Lumpur) was released on 22 March 2023.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Named after Kuala Lumpur in recognition of work done by the GNOME.Asia community, GNOME 44 introduced a new file chooser grid view, updated settings panels, and redesigned accessibility settings.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The new quick settings menu introduced in GNOME 43 was updated, alongside the addition of several new apps and improvements to existing apps.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 45 (Rīga) was released on 20 September 2023.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] It introduced redesigned app styles alongside a new activities button, which replaced both the previous "Activities" label and the app menu with a graphical workspace indicator.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Other updates to the system bar included a new camera usage indicator and a keyboard shortcut to open and close the quick settings menu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 45 also introduced two new image viewer and camera apps, keyboard backlight controls, and numerous enhancements to existing apps.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 46 (Kathmandu) was released on 20 March 2024 and featured an enhanced files app with global search, support for headless remote login via GDM, and a refreshed settings app, amongst many other app changes.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Other system changes included accessibility improvements and experimental support for variable refresh rates.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 47 (Denver) was released on 18 September 2024 and introduced support for user-selected accent colors in Libadwaita applications, allowing greater interface customization.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] It also brought improvements for low-resolution displays through automatic icon scaling, optimizations in screen recording with GPU hardware encoding, and various enhancements to performance, file navigation, and online accounts.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 48 (Bengaluru) was released on 19 March 2025 and is included in Fedora 42 and Ubuntu 25.04.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] This version introduced notification grouping by application (notification stacking), significant performance improvements such as dynamic triple buffering for smoother animations, and optimizations in CPU and memory usage across key system components.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] It also included improvements in file indexing and graphical stability on systems with dedicated GPUs.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 49 (Brescia) was released in September 2025 and is included in Fedora 43 and Ubuntu 25.10.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] It deprecated X11 support, disabling it by default.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] It also replaced the video player Totem and the document viewer Evince with Showtime and Papers, respectively, and introduced shutting down and restarting the computer when logged out.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 50 (Tokyo) was released on 18 March 2026.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 50 removed X11 support from the source code.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] It introduced new parental control features, accessibility improvements such as global options and reduced animations, and optimizations in core applications such as Files (Nautilus) and Calendar.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] It also added improvements to remote desktop with hardware acceleration, expanded graphics support (including enhancements for NVIDIA and variable refresh rates), and new options in system settings.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] By default, GNOME Flashback contains two panels (one on the top, and one to its opposite on the bottom) spanning the width of the screen.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The top panel usually contains navigation menus labeled "Applications" and "Places" in that order, as the "System" menu from GNOME 2.x has been replaced by a control panel in GNOME 3.x.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] These menus hold links to common applications and areas of the file system, respectively.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] A user menu placed on the opposite side of the screen, which has been available since GNOME 2.14 but has become more prominent in GNOME 3.x, holds access to account and system settings as well as options to log out, switch user, and shut down the computer.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The top panel usually contains a clock/calendar and a notification area, which can double as a sort of dock, as well.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The bottom panel is commonly empty by default (other than a set of buttons to navigate between desktops) due to its use in the navigation between windows (windows minimize to the bottom panel by default).
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Users can populate these panels with other completely customizable menus and buttons, including new menus, search boxes, and icons, with the icons in particular (called *launchers*) performing functions similar to the *quick-launch* feature found in the Microsoft Windows 98–Vista taskbar.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Other applications can also be attached to the panels, and the panels are highly reconfigurable: anything on these panels can be moved, removed, or configured in other ways.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The version of GNOME Panel available in the repository for Ubuntu 12.04 offers a modified version of Fallback Mode with the addition of a custom theme and ports of Ubuntu's own Indicators from their old GNOME 2.x desktop.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Trisquel uses Fallback Mode (Flashback) for its main desktop, because GNOME Shell requires 3D acceleration as it relies on graphics composition, while some free software drivers do not support 3D acceleration, among other reasons like more usability and more stability.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Each of the component software products in the GNOME project has its own version number and release schedule.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] However, individual module maintainers coordinate their efforts to create a full GNOME stable release on an approximately six-month schedule, alongside its underlying libraries such as GTK and GLib.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Some experimental projects are excluded from these releases.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Before GNOME 40, GNOME version numbers followed the scheme *v.xx.yy*.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Here, *v* is a major version, which can include large changes such as ABI breakage; these have no regular schedule and occur in response to requirements for large-scale changes.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] *xx* is a minor version, released on the above schedule of approximately every 6 months, in which the 1- or 2-digit number's parity indicates the type of release: if *xx* is even (e.g.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] 3.20) the release is considered stable, whereas if *xx* is odd, it represents a current development snapshot (e.g.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] 3.21) that will eventually evolve into the next stable release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] 3.20.6; these are made on a frequency of weeks in order to fix issues, add non-breaking enhancements, etc.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME 40 started a new versioning scheme in which a single number is incremented with each semi-annual release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The number is followed by a dot and then "alpha", "beta", or "rc" for a development release, or a decimal for a minor stable release (much like the *yy* mentioned previously).
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME releases are made to the main FTP server in the form of source code with configure scripts, which are compiled by operating system vendors and integrated with the rest of their systems before distribution.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Most vendors only use stable and tested versions of GNOME and provide it in the form of easily installed, pre-compiled packages.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The source code of every stable and development version of GNOME is stored in the GNOME git source code repository.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] A number of build scripts (such as JHBuild or formerly GARNOME) are available to help automate the process of compiling the source code.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Since the introduction of Discourse forum in 2019, the discussion moved from mailing lists and in October 2022, the project announced the plan to close all its public mailing lists.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME developers and users gather at an annual GUADEC meeting to discuss the current state and the future direction of GNOME.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME incorporates standards and programs from freedesktop.org to better support interoperability with other desktops.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] GNOME is mainly written in C, XML, C++, C#, HTML, Vala, Python, JavaScript, CSS, and more.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] A number of language bindings are available.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The GLib data structures and utilities library, GObject object and type system and GTK widget toolkit along with the Adwaita design language implemented by libadwaita, comprise the central part of the GNOME development platform.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] The GNOME desktop environment does not consist solely of the graphical control element library GTK and the core applications that make use of it.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] There are quite a few additional software packages that make up the GNOME desktop environment, such as the above.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Wayland support was introduced in GNOME 3.10 and deemed "for the majority of users […] a usable day to day experience" by 3.20, at which point Wayland became the default user session.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] With GNOME 3.24, Wayland compatibility was extended to Nvidia drivers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] In GNOME 3.30 or later, it was possible to run GNOME without X11 running at startup, using only Wayland.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] In GNOME 50, using the X11 session in Mutter is no longer possible, and GNOME became one of the first desktop environments to only support Wayland.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] X11 applications can still be run though XWayland.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] In May 2011 Lennart Poettering proposed systemd as a GNOME dependency.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] As systemd is available only on Linux, the proposal led to a discussion of possibly dropping support for other platforms in future GNOME releases.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Since GNOME 3.2, multiseat support has only been available on systems using systemd.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] In November 2012 the GNOME release team concluded there will be no compile time dependency on systemd for basic functionality, like session tracking.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] For non-basic functionality, like power management, compile time dependency is possible.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] For example, there is no concept of systemd inhibitors in alternatives like consolekit.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] A package manager may want to ensure that the system is not turned off while the upgrade is taking place.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Since GNOME 49 systemd became a stronger dependency.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p01] Adrian Vovk had announced two major changes: GDM is gaining a dependency on systemd’s userdb infrastructure and the builtin service manager of gnome-session is being removed.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] GNOME OS is an operating system designed to provide a streamlined, container-centric platform that serves as both an experimental testbed and a showcase for GNOME's user interface and application ecosystem.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] Unlike many Linux distributions, GNOME OS is not based on other distributions such as Arch Linux, Debian, or Fedora Linux.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] It is built from the ground up using tools like BuildStream, Freedesktop SDK, and GNOME Build Meta, ensuring a clean and consistent environment tailored for GNOME development.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] This approach allows GNOME OS to provide a standardized platform for developers to develop the latest GNOME software without the variability introduced by other distributions.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] While GNOME OS shares similarities with immutable distributions like Fedora Silverblue, it remains distinct in its purpose and design, focusing solely on the GNOME ecosystem.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] The concept of GNOME OS began to take shape around 2010, with discussions and planning sessions focused on creating a more unified and cohesive system for GNOME.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] The vision was inspired by other platforms like Android, WebOS, and MeeGo, with the goal of designing an operating system that could offer a better experience for both users and developers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] In 2012, during the GUADEC conference held in A Coruña, a significant planning session, known as a Birds of a Feather (BoF) session, was conducted on July 30.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] This session brought together key members of the GNOME community to discuss and plan the future direction of GNOME OS.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] The discussions covered several critical areas, including application development, testing, core user experience (UX), pattern language, and support for touch and mobile devices.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] Early OSTree-based build efforts were sometimes informally referred to as "**gnome-ostree**", but the continuous integration pipeline that emerged became known as **GNOME Continuous**, reflecting its primary role as a continuous integration and testing platform for GNOME.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] It was designed to provide a rolling-release environment where developers could test GNOME 3.x features and applications in isolation.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] Technologically, GNOME Continuous adopted OSTree for atomic updates, allowing the system to roll back to previous states if updates failed, ensuring system stability.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] This technology was later popularized by Fedora Silverblue and other immutable Linux distributions.
[src:ubuntu-linux/gnome-p02] GNOME OS first became publicly visible as a testable reference platform around 2020, when the project published a “GNOME OS Nightly” page offering downloadable images and instructions for running the system in virtual machines or on real hardware.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] LTS applies the tenets of reliability engineering to the software development process and software release life cycle.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] Long-term support extends the period of software maintenance; it also alters the type and frequency of software updates (patches) to reduce the risk, expense, and disruption of software deployment, while prioritizing the dependability of the software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] It does not necessarily imply technical support.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] At the beginning of a long-term support period, the software developers impose a feature freeze: They make patches to correct software bugs and vulnerabilities, but do not introduce new features that may cause regression.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] The software maintainer either distributes patches individually, or packages them in maintenance releases, point releases, or service packs.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] At the conclusion of the support period, the product either reaches end-of-life, or receives a reduced level of support for a period of time (e.g., high-priority security patches only).
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] Before upgrading software, a decision-maker might consider the risk and cost of the upgrade.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] As software developers add new features and fix software bugs, they may introduce new bugs or break old functionality.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] When such a flaw occurs in software, it is called a *regression*.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] Two ways that a software publisher or maintainer can reduce the risk of regression are to release major updates less frequently, and to allow users to test an alternate, updated version of the software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] LTS software applies these two risk-reduction strategies.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] The LTS edition of the software is published in parallel with the STS (short-term support) edition.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] Since major updates to the STS edition are published more frequently, it offers LTS users a preview of changes that might be incorporated into the LTS edition when those changes are judged to be of sufficient quality.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] While using older versions of software may avoid the risks associated with upgrading, it may introduce the risk of losing support for the old software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] Long-term support addresses this by assuring users and administrators that the software will be maintained for a specific period of time, and that updates selected for publication will carry a significantly reduced risk of regression.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] The maintainers of LTS software only publish updates that either have low IT risk or that reduce IT risk (such as security patches).
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] Patches for LTS software are published with the understanding that installing them is less risky than not installing them.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] This table only lists software that have a specific LTS version in addition to a normal release cycle.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] Many projects, such as CentOS, provide a long period of support for every release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] , is one year after the release of the next stable version.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] Since Debian 6.0 "Squeeze", LTS support (bug fixes and security patches) was added to all version releases.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] The total LTS support time is generally around 5 years for every version.
[src:ubuntu-linux/long-term-support] and the LTS support is done not by the Debian team but by a separate group of volunteers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] Releases of Ubuntu—a Linux operating system mostly composed of free and open-source software—are made semiannually by Canonical Ltd using the year and month of the release as a version number.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] The first Ubuntu release, for example, was Ubuntu 4.10 and was released on 20 October 2004.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] Consequently, version numbers for future versions are provisional; if the release is delayed until a different month (or even year) than planned, the version number will change accordingly.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] Releases are scheduled every April and October to incorporate new GNOME releases made every March and September.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] Free support is offered and includes security updates for "main" free software packaged.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] Every fourth release, scheduled for April of every even-numbered year, is designated as a long-term support (LTS) release, meaning it receives free support for five years.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] Non-LTS releases are designed as interim releases and receive free support for nine months.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] The Expanded Security Maintenance (ESM) service from the Ubuntu Pro subscription, which is free for personal use on up to five devices, extends long-term support to be ten-years long and include security updates for community-managed "universe" free software packages.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] The Legacy subscription add-on extends long-term support to fifteen years.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] On 19 March 2013, the Ubuntu Technical Board reduced the support period for interim releases from eighteen months to nine.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] For LTS releases 10.04 and earlier, the desktop version received free support for three years, and the server version for five years.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] LTS release 12.04 harmonized the support period to five years and introduced the Extended Security Maintenance service as part of the Ubuntu Advantage subscription service.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] By 26 January 2023, Ubuntu Advantage was rebranded to Ubuntu Pro, and ESM to *Expanded* Security Maintenance as support for the Universe repository was added to the service.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] The paid Legacy Support was introduced on 25 March 2024, extending long-term support by two years, which increased to five years on 13 November 2025.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] After each version of Ubuntu has reached its end-of-life time, its repositories are removed from the main Ubuntu servers and consequently the mirrors.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] Older versions of Ubuntu repositories and releases can be found on the old Ubuntu releases website.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] Ubuntu releases are also given code names, using an adjective and an animal with the same first letter – an alliteration – *e.g.*, "Dapper Drake".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] With the exception of the first two releases, code names are in alphabetical order, and except for the first three releases, the first letters are sequential, allowing a quick determination of which release is newer.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] As of Ubuntu 17.10, the initial letter "rolled over" and returned to "A".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] Names are occasionally chosen so that animal appearance or habits reflects some new feature, *e.g.*, "Koala's favourite leaf is Eucalyptus"; see § Ubuntu 9.10 (Karmic Koala).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p01] Ubuntu releases are often referred to using only the adjective portion of the code name, *e.g.*, "Feisty".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 4.10 (*Warty Warthog*) was released on 20 October 2004 as the inaugural release of Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It received support until 30 April 2006.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It is built upon Debian, with plans for a new release every six months and eighteen months of support thereafter.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 4.10 was offered as a free download and, through Canonical's ShipIt service, was also mailed to users free of charge in CD format.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Similar to UserLinux and unlike other distros at the time—which had the user choose the apps to install—the Debian-based Ubuntu curated "one best FOSS app" for each category, minimizing the amount of questions asked by the installer and the disk space used.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Alternatives and additional software could be installed through Debian's Advanced Package Tool (APT), which featured automatic dependency resolution, a feature then only found in commercial and professional Linux distributions.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu's competitors in the consumer-friendly free-of-charge distributions segment required the user to work out such dependencies themselves and did not use the APT dependency resolution tools due to Debian's notorious complexities and hard installation process, which Ubuntu managed to simplify.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 5.04 (*Hoary Hedgehog*) was released on 8 April 2005.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It received support until 31 October 2006.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Beginning with Ubuntu 5.04, UTF-8 became the default character encoding.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 5.10 (*Breezy Badger*), released on 12 October 2005 and was supported until 13 April 2007.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 6.06 (*Dapper Drake*) released on 1 June 2006 and was the first long-term support (LTS) release, with support continuing until 14 July 2009 for desktops and June 2011 for servers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 6.06 was released behind schedule, having been intended as 6.04.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It is sometimes jokingly described as their first "Late To Ship" (LTS) release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Development was not complete in April 2006 and Mark Shuttleworth approved slipping the release date to June, making it 6.06 instead.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 6.06 did not include a means to install from a USB device, but did for the first time allow installation directly onto removable USB devices.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 6.10 (*Edgy Eft*) released on 26 October 2006 and was supported until 25 April 2008.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 6.10 added several new features including a new Human theme, Upstart init daemon, automated crash reports (Apport), Tomboy note taking application, and F-Spot photo manager.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] EasyUbuntu, a third party program designed to make Ubuntu easier to use, was included in Ubuntu 6.10 as a meta-package.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 7.04 (*Feisty Fawn*), released on 19 April 2007 and was supported until 19 October 2008.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 7.10 (*Gutsy Gibbon*), released on 18 October 2007 and was supported until 18 April 2009.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 7.10 included several new features, among them AppArmor security framework, fast desktop search, a Firefox plug-in manager (Ubufox), a graphical configuration tool for X.Org, full NTFS support (read/write) via NTFS-3G, and a revamped printing system with PDF printing by default.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Compiz Fusion was enabled as default in Ubuntu 7.10 and Fast user switching was added.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 8.04 (*Hardy Heron*), released on 24 April 2008 and was the second long-term support release of Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Support ended on 12 May 2011 for desktops and ended on 9 May 2013 for servers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 8.04 included several new features, among them Tracker desktop search integration, Brasero for disk burning, Transmission for BitTorrent, Vinagre for Virtual Network Computing, system sound through PulseAudio, and Active Directory authentication and login using Likewise Open.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In addition Ubuntu 8.04 included updates for better Tango compliance, various Compiz usability improvements, automatic grabbing and releasing of the mouse cursor when running on a VMware virtual machine, and an easier method to remove Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 8.04 was the first version of Ubuntu to include the Wubi installer on the Live CD that allows Ubuntu to be installed as a folder within Windows, without a disk partition.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The first version of the Ubuntu Netbook Remix was also introduced.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ryan Paul of Ars Technica praised the release's Wubi installer, improved hardware detection, and new software, while criticizing the PulseAudio integration's glitches and lack of configuration.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Paul also criticized Ubuntu's search integration for disadvantages compared to using Beagle—which he found more feature-complete, supported by bundled software, and comparable to the search experiences of other operating systems.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 8.10 (*Intrepid Ibex*), released on 30 October 2008, and was supported until 30 April 2010.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 8.10 introduced several new features including RAID support, improvements to mobile computing, 3G support, and a guest account, which allowed others to use a computer allowing very limited user rights (e.g. accessing the Internet, using software and checking e-mail).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Guest files are saved to a temporary folder wiped when logging out.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Intrepid Ibex also included an encrypted private directory for users, the inclusion of Dynamic Kernel Module Support, a tool that allows kernel drivers to be automatically rebuilt when new kernels are released, and support for creating USB flash drive images.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] On 24 October 2008, Ubuntu 9.04 (*Jaunty Jackalope*) was announced by Mark Shuttleworth and was released on 23 April 2009.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] New features included faster boot times and the integration of web services and applications into the desktop interface.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Because of that, they named it after the mythical jackalope.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It was the first release named after a mythical animal, the second being Utopic Unicorn.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It had a new usplash screen, a new login screen and also support for both Wacom (hotplugging) and netbooks.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It also included a new notification system, *Notify OSD*, and themes.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It marked the first time that all of Ubuntu's core development moved to the GNU Bazaar distributed version control system.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 9.04 was the first version to support the ARM architecture with native support for ARMv5EL and ARMv6EL-VFP.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 9.10 (*Karmic Koala*) was released on 29 October 2009, with support until April 2011.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The desktop installation of Ubuntu 9.10 replaced Pidgin with Empathy Instant Messenger as its default instant messaging client.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The default filesystem is ext4, and the Ubuntu One client, which interfaces with Canonical's new online storage system, is installed by default.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It introduced Grub 2 beta as its default bootloader.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It also replaced Add/Remove Programs (gnome-app-install) with Ubuntu Software Center, while Canonical stated their intention to possibly replace Synaptic, Software Sources, Gdebi and Update Manager in Ubuntu 10.04.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Karmic Koala also includes a slideshow during the installation process (through ubiquity-slideshow) that highlights applications and features in Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In an announcement to the community on 20 February 2009, Shuttleworth explained that 9.10 would focus on improvements in cloud computing on the server using Eucalyptus, a new theme, as well as further improvements in boot speed and development of the Ubuntu Netbook Remix.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The new theme was later delayed to version 10.04, and only minor revisions were made to the default theme.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Other graphical improvements included a new set of boot up and shutdown splash screens, a new login screen with a new transition into the desktop and greatly improved performance on Intel graphics chip-sets.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In June 2009, Canonical created the One Hundred Paper Cuts project, focusing developers to fix minor usability issues.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Shuttleworth first announced Ubuntu 10.04 (*Lucid Lynx*) on 19 September 2009 at the Atlanta Linux Fest before it was released on 29 April 2010 as Ubuntu's third long-term support (LTS) release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Canonical provided support for the desktop version of Ubuntu 10.04 until 9 May 2013 and for the server version until 30 April 2015.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The release included improved support for Nvidia proprietary graphics drivers while switching to the open source Nvidia graphics driver, Nouveau, by default.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Plymouth was also introduced, allowing boot animations.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It also included a video editor for the first time by including Pitivi.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] GIMP was replaced with F-Spot due to the former's complexity and file size.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The distribution also included integrated interfaces for posting to social media.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The new theme met with mixed critical responses.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] *Ars Technica'*s Ryan Paul said: "The new themes and updated color palette are nice improvement for Ubuntu ...
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] After testing the new theme for several hours, I feel like it's a step forward, but it still falls a bit short of my expectations." One aspect of controversy from the new design was the placement of the window-control buttons on the left instead of on the right side of the windows.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] I believe the fans are divided right now.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The naming of Ubuntu 10.10 (*Maverick Meerkat*) was announced by Shuttleworth on 2 April 2010, along with the release's goals of improving the netbook experience and a server focus on hybrid cloud computing.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] New features included the new Unity interface for the Netbook Edition, a new default photo manager, Shotwell, replacing F-Spot, the ability to purchase applications in the Software Center, and an official Ubuntu font used by default.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The naming of Ubuntu 11.04 (*Natty Narwhal*) was announced on 17 August 2010 by Shuttleworth, and was released on 28 April 2011 with support until 28 October 2012.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 11.04 used the Unity user interface instead of GNOME 2 as default.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The move to Unity was controversial as some GNOME developers feared it would fracture the community and marginalize GNOME Shell.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 11.04 employed Banshee as the default music player, replacing Rhythmbox.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Other new applications included OpenStack, Firefox 4, and LibreOffice, which replaced OpenOffice.org.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The Ubuntu Netbook Edition was merged into the desktop edition.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Jesse Smith of DistroWatch criticized the instability of the release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The naming of Ubuntu 11.10 (*Oneiric Ocelot*) was announced on 7 March 2011 by Mark Shuttleworth.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] He explained that Oneiric means "dreamy".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 11.10 was released on 13 October 2011, and was supported until 9 May 2013.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In April 2011, Shuttleworth announced that Ubuntu 11.10 would not include the classic GNOME desktop as a fall back to Unity.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Instead, 11.10 included a 2D version of Unity as a fallback for computers that lacked the hardware resources for the Compiz-based 3D version.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Shuttleworth also confirmed that Unity in Ubuntu 11.10 would run as a shell for GNOME 3 on top of GNOME 3 libraries, unlike in Ubuntu 11.04 where it ran as a shell for GNOME 2.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Meanwhile, users were able to install the entire GNOME 3 stack along with GNOME Shell directly from the Ubuntu repositories.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In May 2011, it was announced that Pitivi would be no longer part of the Ubuntu ISO, starting with Ubuntu 11.10 Oneiric Ocelot.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The reasons given for removing it included poor user reception, lack of fit with the default user-case for Ubuntu, lack of polish and the application's lack of development maturity.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Other changes included the removal of the Synaptic package manager, and removing Computer Janitor, as it caused broken systems for users.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Déjà Dup was added as Ubuntu's backup program.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Mozilla Thunderbird replaced the GNOME Evolution email client.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 12.04 LTS (*Precise Pangolin*) is the fourth long-term support (LTS) version of Ubuntu, released on 26 April 2012.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It is named after the pangolin anteater.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The support period for the desktop version was increased to five years from three years to match the server version with this release, ending on 28 April 2017.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Canonical continued to offer extended security maintenance to Advantage customers for an additional two years.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Shuttleworth claimed that the HUD will ultimately replace menus in Unity applications.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] This release also switched the default media player from Banshee back to Rhythmbox and dropped the Tomboy note-taking application along with the supporting Mono framework.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It also shipped with IPv6 privacy extensions, a feature introduced in 11.10, turned on by default.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] On 23 April 2012, Shuttleworth announced Ubuntu 12.10 (*Quantal Quetzal*) as the first of 4 releases that will culminate in LTS 14.04 and refresh the look, with work to be done on typography and iconography.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The release takes its name from the quetzal, a species of Central American birds.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In September 2012, Canonical's Kate Stewart announced that the Ubuntu 12.10 image would not fit on a compact disc.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] However, a third-party project has created a version of Ubuntu 12.10 that fits on a CD with LZMA2 compression instead of the DEFLATE compression used on the official Ubuntu DVD image.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In the same month, it was announced that the version of Unity to be shipped with Ubuntu 12.10 would by default include searches from Amazon.com for searched terms.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] This move caused immediate controversy among Ubuntu users, particularly with regard to privacy issues and European Directive 95/46/EC, and caused Shuttleworth to issue a statement indicating that this feature is not adware and labelled many of the objections as Fear, uncertainty, and doubt.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Regardless, users filed a Launchpad bug report on the feature requesting that it be made a separate lens (mode for the search engine) and not included with general desktop searches for files, directories and applications.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The degree of community push-back on the issue resulted in plans by the developers to make the dash and where it searches user-configurable via a GUI-setting dialogue.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Despite concerns that the setting dialogue would not make the release, it was completed and is present in 12.10.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In reviewing Ubuntu 12.10 at the end of October 2012 for DistroWatch, Jesse Smith raised concerns that "Canonical reserves the right to share our keystrokes, search terms and IP address with a number of third parties", and criticized the low performance and instability of the release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In early November, the Electronic Frontier Foundation criticized how the release loaded products from Amazon through HTTP, subject to eavesdropping.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Jim Lynch gave a favorable review in December while noting concerns of software bloat.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The Wubi installer for Windows was dropped due to its incompatibility with Windows 8 and general lack of support and development.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It included Unity 7, which had many performance improvements, and searching of photos and social media posts from the Dash.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] On 23 April 2013, Ubuntu 13.10 (*Saucy Salamander*) was announced by Mark Shuttleworth, and it was released on 17 October 2013.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Consideration was given to changing the default browser from Mozilla Firefox to Chromium, but problems with updates to Ubuntu's Chromium package caused developers to retain Firefox for this release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Similarly, the aging X Window System (X11) was intended to be replaced with the Mir display server, with X11 programs to have operated through the XMir compatibility layer.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] However, after the development of XMir ran into "outstanding technical difficulties" for multiple monitors, Canonical decided to postpone the default use of Mir in Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Mir was still be released as the default display server for Ubuntu Touch 13.10.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Joey Sneddon of *OMG Ubuntu* criticized the new Smart Scopes feature, noting that internet search engines turn in more useful and better organized results and recommended selectively disabling individual scopes to reduce the noise factor.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Jim Lynch of *Linux Desktop Reviews* described the release as "boring" and the Smart Scopes feature as "very useful".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In its year-end *Readers Choice Awards*, *Linux Journal* readers voted Ubuntu as Best Linux Distribution and Best Desktop Distribution for 2013.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Mark Shuttleworth announced on 31 October 2011 that by Ubuntu 14.04, Ubuntu would support smartphones, tablets, TVs and smart screens.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] On 18 October 2013, Shuttleworth announced that Ubuntu 14.04 (*Trusty Tahr*) would focus on "performance, refinement, maintainability, [*sic*] technical debt" and encouraged the developers to make "conservative choices".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Support ended on 25 April 2019, after which extended security maintenance was available to Ubuntu Advantage customers for two more years.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] However, in September 2021, Canonical announced that it would extend LTS support for the 14.04 and 16.04 to a total of 10 years, extending ESM support for 14.04 until April 2024.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In November 2025, Canonical announced they are further expanding LTS support to 15 years through their Legacy add-on, extending support for 14.04 through April 2029.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The development cycle for this release focused on the tablet interface, specifically the Nexus 7 and Nexus 10 tablets.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 14.04 reintroduced the ability to turn off the global menu system and use locally integrated menus instead for individual applications.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Other features included a Unity 8 developers' preview, new mobile applications, a redesigned Startup Disk Creator tool, a new forked version of the GNOME Control Center called the Unity Control Center, and default SSD TRIM support.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] In reviewing Ubuntu 14.04 LTS in April 2014, Jim Lynch concluded: "While there are not a lot of amazing new features in this release, there are quite a few very useful and needed tweaks that add up to a much better desktop experience.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Ubuntu 14.10 "Utopic Unicorn" was released on 23 October.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Scott Gilbertson of The Register found little changes in the release (which did not include a new wallpaper) as developers focused on developing the future Unity 8 desktop environment and Mir display server, noting that the release marked the Ubuntu project's 10-year anniversary.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] On 20 October 2014, Shuttleworth announced that Ubuntu 15.04 would be named *Vivid Vervet*.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] With this release, systemd became the default init implementation, replacing Upstart.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Though Shuttleworth dislikes systemd, the change was made due to Ubuntu's reliance on Debian, which had switched to systemd.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The Unity 7 desktop environment may now always show menu items.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] The beta version defaulted to showing menu items in the application window instead of the top bar, a change reverted in the stable release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Jesse Smith of DistroWatch praised the stability of the release, especially amid the switch to systemd.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Scott Gilbertson of Ars Technica criticised inconsistencies in the desktop environment amid Canonical's development focus on the upcoming Unity 8.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Shuttleworth announced on 4 May 2015 that Ubuntu 15.10 would be called *Wily Werewolf*.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] He initially expressed hope that the release would include the Mir display server, but it was released on 22 October 2015 without Mir.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] It eliminated the disappearing window edge scrollbars in favour of the upstream GNOME scrollbars, a move designed to save developer time in creating patches and updates.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p02] Vaughan-Nichols of ZDNET praised the release for its integration of cloud services, such as the new Ubuntu OpenStack cloud deployment and management tool "OpenStack Autopilot", as well as its server tools, especially Ubuntu's machine container hypervisor, LXD, included by default in 15.10.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Shuttleworth announced on 21 October 2015 that Ubuntu 16.04 LTS would be called *Xenial Xerus* and include an option for Unity 8.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] In September 2021, Canonical announced that it would extend LTS support for the 14.04 and 16.04 to a total of 10 years, extending the ESM support date for 16.04 until April 2026.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The release adds support for Ceph and ZFS filesystems, the LXD hypervisor for OpenStack, and Snap packages.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This release has online Dash search results disabled by default in Unity 7, does not support the AMD Catalyst (fglrx) driver for AMD/ATI graphics cards, and instead recommends the Radeon and AMDGPU alternatives.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] It also replaced the Ubuntu Software Center with GNOME Software (rebranded as "Ubuntu Software") and eliminated Empathy and Brasero from the ISO file.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Mark Shuttleworth announced on 21 April 2016 that Ubuntu 16.10 would be called *Yakkety Yak*.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] On 17 October 2016, Mark Shuttleworth announced that the codename of Ubuntu 17.04, released on 13 April 2017, would be *Zesty Zapus*.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This release dropped support for the 32-bit PowerPC architecture, following the same move by the upstream Debian project.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Other changes include the default DNS resolver now being *systemd-resolved*, Linux kernel 4.10, and included support for printers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Reviewers noted that this was likely to be the last version of Ubuntu to ship with Unity 7 by default before Ubuntu's switch to GNOME, matching the end of the alphabet in Ubuntu's codename scheme.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Artful Aardvark was announced via Launchpad on 21 April 2017 instead of on Shuttleworth's blog as had been the case in the past.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Critics praised the smooth transition to GNOME and the significance of the release's changes.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This is the first release of Ubuntu to use the GNOME Shell interface, and the first release to replace X11 with the Wayland display server.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] In May 2017, Ken VanDine, a Canonical Software Engineer on the Ubuntu desktop team tasked with the switch to GNOME, confirmed that the intention is to ship the most current version of GNOME, with very few changes from a stock installation.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This release also dropped 32-bit desktop images; other images' 32-bit versions remain.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 18.04 LTS Bionic Beaver, the seventh LTS release, is a long-term support version that was announced on 24 October 2017 on Shuttleworth's blog and released on 26 April 2018.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 18.04 LTS had normal LTS support for five years until May 2023 and has paid ESM support available from Canonical for an additional five years until April 2028.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] New features include colour emoji, a new To-Do application preinstalled in the default installation, the "Minimal Install" option in the system installer, which only installs a web browser and system tools, and new command-line system installer for Ubuntu Server.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This release employed Linux kernel 4.15, which incorporated a CPU controller for the cgroup v2 interface, AMD secure memory encryption support and improved SATA Link Power Management.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 18.04 LTS's default display server was returned to Xorg for more stability; Wayland was still included as part of the default install.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] For the first time some bundled applications were delivered by default as snaps.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Plans to include a new theme, *Communitheme* (now *Yaru*), created by the Ubuntu community, were announced on 5 February 2018.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] However, Ubuntu 18.04 LTS did not include it, citing "outstanding bugs, a lack of broader testing, as well as ongoing gaps in corner-case usage." The new theme was available as a Snap package instead.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Shuttleworth announced Ubuntu 18.10 *Cosmic Cuttlefish* on 8 May 2018.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Installation speeds are faster due to the use of a lossless compression algorithm known as Zstandard.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Startup speeds of pre-installed Snap applications were also improved.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 18.10 includes a new theme, *Yaru*, as the default theme, along with its accompanying icon theme, *Suru*.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Shuttleworth announced Ubuntu 19.04 *Disco Dingo* on 20 October 2018.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] It incorporates Linux kernel 5.0, which adds support for AMD FreeSync technology for liquid-crystal displays, Raspberry Pi touchscreens, Adiantum encryption, Btrfs swap files as well as many USB 3.2 and Type-C improvements and several other new hardware.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] It uses GNOME 3.32, which includes a new icon set, night light intensity control, advanced application permissions, favoriting files, and a new header bar as well as 'find' and 'read only' modes in the default terminal emulator.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Version 19 of the open-source graphics drivers Mesa is natively available in this version of Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Furthermore, the Grub menu now allows a 'safe graphics' mode in case of issues with graphics cards or graphics drivers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Geoclue integration and fractional scaling in the GNOME Shell for HiDPI displays are also included.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Improvements for running Ubuntu on a VMWare virtual machine include integration of open-vm-tools within Ubuntu, allowing for bi-directional clipboard and file sharing.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu Server 19.04 updated QEMU to version 3.1, allowing for creation of a virtual 3D GPU inside QEMU virtual machines. libvirt was updated to version 5.0 and Samba was updated to version 4.10.x.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Samba and its dependencies were updated to Python 3, with the exception of tdb, which still builds a Python 2 package, namely *python-tdb*.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu Server 19.04 includes the latest OpenStack release, Stein, and has vSwitch version 2.11.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Shuttleworth announced Ubuntu 19.10, codenamed *Eoan Ermine* on 3 April 2019.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] It uses Linux kernel 5.3 which, among others, introduces compatibility for third-generation Ryzen CPU motherboards and associated Intel Wireless devices as well as AMD's 7 nm Navi GPUs.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Experimental support for the ZFS filesystem is now available from the installer.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Proprietary Nvidia graphics drivers are now bundled with the installer in place of the open-source Nouveau drivers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Support for the Raspberry Pi 4 platform was added.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The installation media now uses LZ4 compression which, compared to the previously used compression algorithm, gzip, offers faster installation times.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This was decided following benchmarking of a variety of compression algorithms conducted by the Ubuntu kernel team.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Kernel load and decompression times were tested and LZ4 was found to offer decompression as much as seven times faster.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 19.10 uses GNOME 3.34 which, among others, adds the ability to group application icons into folders, introduces a background settings panel and a separate Night Light tab as well as improves upon performance and smoothness.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] A new Yaru light theme was introduced with this release as well.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] In a November 2019 *Ars Technica* review by Scott Gilbertson, he concluded, "Ubuntu 19.10 is unusual for an October Ubuntu release in that I would call it a must-have upgrade.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] On 17 August 2019, Ubuntu 20.04 LTS, codenamed *Focal Fossa* was announced by Shuttleworth.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] It was released on 23 April 2020, and as a long-term support release, it received maintenance updates for 5 years until April 2025.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This release is based on Linux kernel 5.4 LTS which adds support for new hardware including Intel's Comet Lake and Tiger Lake CPUs, Qualcomm's Snapdragon 835 and 855 SoCs as well as AMD Navi 12 and 14 GPUs.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Python 2 is no longer included by default.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This release refreshed the Yaru theme and uses GNOME 3.36 which revamped the login screen.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Improvements have also been made to the system menu and the installation screen, which now shows a graphical drive checking routine.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The ZFS file system is now offered as an option in the installer and tools for it are now bundled.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The OEM logo is now displayed during boot.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu Software will now only install packages from the Snap Store and provide an option for selecting the desired release channel to install from.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This release also ended all support for the 32-bit architecture.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] DEB files now open in Archive Manager by default.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Reviewers praised the stability, polish and speed of the release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Joey Sneddon of *OMG Ubuntu* noted the significant number of major changes compared to other recent LTS releases.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 20.10, codenamed *Groovy Gorilla*, was released on 22 October 2020.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This release is based on GNOME 3.38 and Linux kernel 5.8 which includes support for USB4, AMD Zen 3 CPUs, Intel Ice Lake and Tiger Lake processors, and initial support for booting Power10 processors.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] In addition, nftables is now the default firewall backend, replacing iptables.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 20.10 is the first release to feature desktop images for the Raspberry Pi 4 (4 GB and 8 GB models) and the Compute Module 4.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Older Pi models with less memory are not officially supported.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 21.04, codenamed *Hirsute Hippo*, was released on 22 April 2021.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] It uses Linux kernel 5.11 which introduces smartcard authentication, support for Intel's Software Guard Extensions and improved support for AMD CPUs and GPUs.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Wayland is now used as the default on hardware without Nvidia graphics processors.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Support for drag and drop from the file manager to the desktop was also added.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] An update to GNOME 40 was canceled due to questions about the stability of the GTK4 toolkit, a major GNOME interface redesign, and its unknown impact on GNOME extensions and Ubuntu's default Yaru GTK theme.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] In a review, Joey Sneddon of *OMG Ubuntu* praised the stability and new features: "But it's not a release totally devoid of value.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 21.04 features a striking new dark theme and makes a raft of smaller UI tweaks that add up to an impressive, polished whole.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 21.10, codenamed *Impish Indri*, was released on 14 October 2021.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] It uses Linux kernel 5.13, which introduces rudimentary support for Apple M1 chips, FreeSync HDMI support for AMD GPUs, a new "Landlock" security module and support for several new hardware.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This release transitions from GNOME 3.38 to GNOME 40, which introduces a horizontal workspace switcher and an improved Activities Overview design.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The Ubuntu Dock remains vertically placed on the left of the screen and now features separators between pinned and running applications, a persistent trash can icon and USB drive shortcuts.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] After logging in, the user will be shown the desktop instead of the Activities Overview.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Despite Ubuntu 21.10 shipping with GNOME 40, a few GNOME 41 apps are available.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] A Firefox Snap is now installed by default on Ubuntu 21.10 instead of the deb package, which remained available.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Furthermore, the Nvidia proprietary drivers now support Wayland sessions.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The default Yaru theme was also updated with new icons and Zstd compression was enabled in the main archive, making installations faster.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 22.04, codenamed *Jammy Jellyfish*, was released on 21 April 2022, and is a long-term support release, supported for five years, until April 2027.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 22.04 LTS Desktop uses Linux kernel 5.17 for newer hardware and a rolling HWE (hardware enablement) kernel based on version 5.15 for other hardware; Ubuntu 22.04 LTS Server uses version 5.15, while Ubuntu Cloud and Ubuntu for IoT use an optimized kernel based on version 5.15.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] It updates Python to 3.10 and Ruby to 3.0.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The desktop is a mix of GNOME 41 and 42 applications to avoid libadwaita.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The default web browser, Firefox, is only available as a snap package and the release repositories no longer provide an alternative .deb package.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This release includes two Yaru themes, light and dark, with a choice of ten different accent colors for customization.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] A planned notification asking to enable Ubuntu Pro, a free-for-home-use rebrand of Ubuntu Advantage, was dropped from the release after user backlash.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] In a poll conducted by DistroWatch, 70% of readers expressed dislike at Ubuntu migrating packages to being snap-only.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 22.10, codenamed *Kinetic Kudu*, was released on 20 October 2022.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] It uses Linux kernel 5.19, which improves the power efficiency on Intel-based computers and supports multithreaded decompression.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 23.04 *Lunar Lobster* is an interim release, released on 20 April 2023 and supported for nine months until 20 January 2024.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The release also provides support for Microsoft Azure Active Directory (a.k.a.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Entra ID), which allows users with Microsoft 365 Enterprise plans to authenticate the Ubuntu desktops using common credentials.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The default font has been updated to be slimmer and sharper.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu* wrote, "if you asked me to describe Ubuntu 23.04 in one word I'd choose: "improvement".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 23.10 *Mantic Minotaur* is an interim release, originally released on 12 October 2023, and supported for nine months until July 2024.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This release incorporates a new App Center built in Flutter that replaces Ubuntu Software, TPM disk encryption, a separated firmware updater, Netplan as the default network configuration tool, and support for Raspberry Pi 5.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The installer can now update itself, support guided ZFS installation, and defaults to a minimal installation, which doesn't include apps deemed non-essential such as LibreOffice, Mozilla Thunderbird, Rhythmbox, and Calendar.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Out-of-the-box support for installing .deb package files graphically was removed; however, the dialog for choosing an alternative app to open the file still recommended opening with the App Center.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This would lead to uproar when the behavior was left unchanged in the next release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This version also includes an upgrade to GNOME 45, which replaces the top-left corner's app name display with an indicator of the workspace being used, adds a camera usage indicator, a new camera app named "Snapshot", and a new image viewer app.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Sidebars are now as tall as their windows as part of design polishing.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Approximately 6 hours after release, the download link to Ubuntu 23.10 was removed due to hate speech in an externally-sourced Ukrainian translation of the installer.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 24.04 *Noble Numbat* is a long-term support release that was released on 25 April 2024.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] It is based on systemd v255.4 and Linux kernel 6.8, which includes support for more gamepads and better swap memory handling.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Raspberry Pi users no longer need to install its own package for bluetooth support, and the year 2038 problem has been patched for 32-bit armhf systems, which will no longer have their own images in future major releases.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The release coincides with the release of Netplan v1.0, the default network configuration tool since 23.10.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] System image size has been reduced by 200 MB.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] As part of an upgrade to GNOME 46, many apps have been updated to use libadwaita and GTK4.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Nautilus, the file manager, has received several quality-of-life features, and Wi-Fi settings now include an option to generate a QR code for network credentials.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Notifications now include a header for the sender app's name, settings have been reorganized, touch users now tap to click by default, and users can now log in from a remote desktop.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Cheese, a Photo Booth-like camera app, has been replaced by GNOME Snapshot in the extended install, and GNOME Games is now never bundled on install.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Thunderbird is now provided as only its snap version.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Abishek of *It's Foss News* strongly criticized the LTS release for not changing behavior from 23.10, the last release, that by default made users unable to graphically install .deb packages, the most popular format for distributing software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Conversely, *It's Foss* praised other aspects of the release as "a near-perfect upgrade".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] By July 15, the App Center received the ability to install .deb packages (while providing a warning), though they still cannot be managed even if installed from the App Center's store.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 24.10 *Oracular Oriole* is an interim release, released on 10 October 2024, marking the 20th anniversary of the Ubuntu project; to commemorate, the release includes a selectable retro theme (wallpaper, accent color, and startup sound).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu's GNOME customizations were moved to a separate Settings section, a Security Center was added that features fine-grained app-by-app permissions control, the dock shows progress bars for updates to snap apps, and the App Center now supports graphically installing DEB files.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The release uses Wayland by default on Nvidia GPUs and ships GNOME 47.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Additionally, it includes JPEG XL support by default and replaces the archived Mozilla Location Service with beaconDB.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 25.10 *Questing Quokka* was released on 9 October 2025.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Update notification is now done through a notification and tray applet instead of a window that steals input focus; Ubuntu plans to work on a different solution when Wayland protocols allow for better control of the window to focus.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Icons on the desktop now have improved keyboard navigation and screenreader announcements.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] TPM-backed full-disk encryption has been added as an experimental installer option along with support in Firmware Updater and Security Center.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] A new boot spinner fixes distracting visual glitches, and the dock icon outline now aligns with the edge of the dock, shipped along with updates to the default Yaru theme (including a new trash can).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The release adopts Dracut for initramfs generation, chrony for time synchronization, and Rust rewrites of fundamental command-line utilities: sudo-rs for sudo and rust-coreutils to replace GNU Core Utilities.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] APT 3.1 is customized to include the upcoming history-related features as an "easter egg"—without documentation.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] In a push to cut down on size, wget was removed from the default server install in favor of wcurl, as well as Byobu and GNU Screen in favor of tmux.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The Raspberry Pi image is now consistent with the "minimal" software set option in the desktop installer and uses a backup and boot-testing mechanism to improve booting reliability in a new process dubbed "tryboot".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] For RISC-V processors, the release raises profile requirements to RVA23, which was not implemented in any on-market hardware as of 9 October.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ptyxis replaces GNOME Terminal as the default terminal emulator, providing container and remote connection support along with performance improvements.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Loupe replaces Eye of GNOME as the default image viewer.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu* expressed annoyance at being unable to run custom commands at login with the new interface.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Initially, Ubuntu 25.10 could not install flatpaks due to an AppArmor issue.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Some Ubuntu 25.10 systems could not automatically check for software updates due to a bug in rust-coreutils's version of the `date` command fixed on 22 October.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Manual updates such as updates done through the `apt` command were not affected.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Ubuntu 26.04 *Resolute Raccoon* was released on 23 April 2026 and users were officially allowed to upgrade from 25.10 on 14 May.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] 24.04 LTS installations were expected to be able to upgrade in August with the release of 26.04.1.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The codename was selected by and as a tribute to the Debian and Ubuntu release manager, Steve Langasek, before his death.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] This version incorporates Linux 7.0 and GNOME 50, which removed support for Xorg/X11.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Recommended system requirements were raised to 6 GB RAM to reflect typical workloads.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Sudo was configured to show asterisks when typing by default.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] The desktop UI was updated with greater contrast and consistency, more colorful folder icons, and a new boot animation inspired by the Resolute Raccoon mascot.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Showtime replaced Totem video player, and Resources replaces System Monitor and Power Statistics.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Global search can now search for available Snap applications and the web.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Software & Updates, which manages package repositories, was dropped from the default installation; Ubuntu Pro status is now managed by Security Center, along with disk encryption.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu-version-history-p03] Canonical revealed the codename for Ubuntu 26.10 on April 20, 2026, and it is officially “Stonking Stingray.” According to the company’s schedule, its release is expected on October 15, 2026.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu is published on a six-month release cycle, with long-term support (LTS) versions issued every two years.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Canonical provides security updates and support until each release reaches its designated end-of-life (EOL), with optional extended support available through the Ubuntu Pro and Expanded Security Maintenance (ESM) services.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu can be installed directly on hardware or run within a virtual machine.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] It is widely used for cloud computing, with integration support for platforms such as OpenStack.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] It is also one of the most popular Linux distributions for general desktop use, supported by extensive online communities such as Ask Ubuntu, and has spawned numerous community-maintained variants.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The name "Ubuntu" comes from the Nguni philosophy of **ubuntu**, which translates roughly as "humanity to others" or "I am what I am because of who we all are".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In April 2004, Mark Shuttleworth invited a dozen Debian developers to his London flat, where they brainstormed and laid out the distinguishing features of what would become Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Shuttleworth chose the "Ubuntu" name for his South African roots and to emphasize community.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] To fund the project, Shuttleworth created Canonical Ltd. to employ the developers using his fortune from selling Thawte to Verisign.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] For the first year, the company had no physical offices and employees used online platforms to coordinate, fostering transparency.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The group set a six-month deadline and decided only to announce Ubuntu during its first release—October 2004: "Warty Warthog".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] On 8 July 2005, Shuttleworth and Canonical launched the newly-created Ubuntu Foundation and provided initial funding of US$10 million.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The purpose of the foundation is to ensure the support and development for all future versions of Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Mark Shuttleworth described the foundation's goal as to ensure the continuity of the Ubuntu project.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] On 12 March 2009, Ubuntu announced developer support for third-party cloud management platforms, such as those used at Amazon EC2.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2011, Ubuntu's default desktop was changed from GNOME 2 to the in-house Unity instead of GNOME 3.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2014, Canonical announced Snappy Ubuntu Core, an immutable OS designed for use in embedded systems, along with its new package manager named "Snappy" derived from the Ubuntu Phone project.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] By the release of Ubuntu 16.04, the package management system was renamed "Snap" and supported desktop apps, becoming an alternative to Flatpak.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] After nearly 6.5 years, the default desktop was changed back to GNOME 3 in 2017, upon the release of version 17.10.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu, since version 16.04.5, requires a 2 GB or larger installation medium.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The last release of Ubuntu available on a minimal CD was 18.04.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] 32-bit x86 processors were supported up to Ubuntu 18.04.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] It was decided to support "legacy software", i.e. select 32-bit i386 packages, for Ubuntu 19.10 (since out of support) and 20.04 LTS.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2022, Ubuntu consolidated its extended security maintenance and hardening services into the Ubuntu Pro subscriptions, including LivePatch, a feature that allows devices to perform select security updates without reboots, available free-of-charge for personal use on up to five machines.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In June 2023, Canonical announced Ubuntu Core Desktop, an immutable desktop OS, completely made of snap packages like Ubuntu Core and slated for release along Ubuntu 24.04 LTS.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Its release was indefinitely delayed, as the vision for major advantages had not yet been fully realized.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] After a rise in the popularity of cryptocurrency scam packages, the Snap Store started requiring manual approval for new applications in March 2024.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] On 9 August 2024, Ubuntu announced a change in policy to always use the latest upstream version of the Linux kernel at the time of each Ubuntu release, even if the kernel code has not seen a stable release and is still in release candidate status.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Support for the X11 windowing system was dropped in favour of the alternative Wayland with Ubuntu version 25.10 in 2025, which shipped with GNOME 49 which had made the change.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu is built on Debian's architecture and infrastructure, and comprises Linux server, desktop, and discontinued phone and tablet operating system versions.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] As of version 24.10, a default installation of Ubuntu contains a minimal selection of software, namely a web browser (Firefox), and basic GNOME utilities (including the desktop).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Many additional software packages are accessible from the built-in Ubuntu Software (previously Ubuntu Software Center), as well as any other APT-based package management tools.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Many additional software packages that are no longer installed by default, such as Evolution, GIMP, Pidgin, and Synaptic, are still accessible in the repositories and installable by the main tool or by any other APT-based package management tool.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Cross-distribution snap packages and Flatpaks are also available, that both allow installing software, such as some of Microsoft's software, in most of the major Linux operating systems (such as any currently supported Ubuntu version and in Fedora).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The default file manager is GNOME Files, formerly called Nautilus.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] All of the application software installed by default is free software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In addition, Ubuntu redistributes some hardware drivers that are available only in binary format, but such packages are clearly marked in the restricted component.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Current long-term support (LTS) releases are supported for five years, and are released every two years.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Since the release of Ubuntu 6.06, every fourth release receives long-term support.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Long-term support includes updates for new hardware, security patches, and updates to the 'Ubuntu stack' (cloud computing infrastructure).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The first LTS releases were supported for three years on the desktop and five years on the server; since Ubuntu 12.04 LTS, desktop support for LTS releases was increased to five years as well.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] LTS releases get regular point releases with support for new hardware and integration of all the updates published in that series to date.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu packages are based on Debian's unstable branch, which are synchronized every six months.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Both distributions use Debian's package management tools (e.g.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] APT and GNOME Software) and deb format of packages.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Debian and Ubuntu packages are not necessarily binary compatible with each other, however, some packages may need to be rebuilt from source to be used in Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Many Ubuntu developers are also maintainers of key packages within Debian.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu cooperates with Debian by pushing changes back to Debian, although there has been criticism that this does not happen often enough.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ian Murdock, the founder of Debian, had expressed concern about Ubuntu packages potentially diverging too far from Debian to remain compatible.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Before release, packages are imported from Debian unstable continuously and merged with Ubuntu-specific modifications.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] At some point during the release process, the Debian Import Freeze is implemented.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] This prevents the automatic import of packages from Debian without an explicit request from a developer.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In combination with other freezes, this helps packagers ensure that frozen features interoperate well together.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] All official Ubuntu packages are available from hundreds of mirrors worldwide.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] As of 30 March 2025, there were a total of 617 Ubuntu mirrors operating.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] User programs run with low privileges and cannot corrupt the operating system or other users' files.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] For increased security, the sudo tool is used to assign temporary privileges for performing administrative tasks, which allows the root account to remain locked and helps prevent inexperienced users from inadvertently making catastrophic system changes or opening security holes.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Polkit is also being widely implemented into the desktop.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Most network ports are closed by default to prevent hacking.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] A built-in firewall, Uncomplicated Firewall, allows end-users who install network servers to control access.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu compiles its packages using GCC features such as PIE and buffer overflow protection to harden its software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] These extra features greatly increase security at the performance expense of 0.01% in 64-bit.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu also supports full disk encryption, as well as encryption of the home and private directories.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The system requirements vary among Ubuntu products.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] For the Ubuntu desktop release 22.04 LTS (and still for 24.04.3), a PC with at least 2 GHz dual-core processor, 4 GB of RAM and 25 GB of free disk space is recommended.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] For less powerful computers, there are other Ubuntu distributions such as Lubuntu and Xubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu also supports the ARM architecture.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] It is also available on Power ISA, while older PowerPC architecture was at one point unofficially supported, and now newer Power ISA CPUs (POWER8) are supported.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The x86-64 ("AMD64") architecture is also officially supported.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Live images are the typical way for users to assess and subsequently install Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] These can be downloaded as a disk image (.iso) and subsequently burnt to a DVD or USB flash drive and then booted.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Other methods include running the live version via Ventoy, UNetbootin, Universal USB Installer, or Startup Disk Creator (a pre-installed tool on Ubuntu, available on machines already running the OS) directly from a USB drive (making, respectively, a live DVD or live USB medium).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Running Ubuntu in this way is slower than running it from a hard drive, but does not alter the computer unless specifically instructed by the user.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] If the user chooses to boot the live image rather than execute an installer at boot time, there is still the option to then use the Ubuntu Desktop Installer once booted into the live environment.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The Ubuntu Desktop Installer replaced the former Ubiquity installer since Ubuntu 23.04.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Disk images of all current and past versions are available for download at the Ubuntu web site.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Additionally, USB flash drive installations can be used to boot Ubuntu and Kubuntu in a way that allows permanent saving of user settings and portability of the USB-installed system between physical machines (however, the computers' BIOS must support booting from USB).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In newer versions of Ubuntu, the Ubuntu Live USB creator can be used to install Ubuntu on a USB drive (with or without a live CD or DVD).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Creating a bootable USB drive with persistence is as simple as dragging a slider to determine how much space to reserve for persistence; for this, Ubuntu employs casper.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu divides most software into four domains to reflect differences in licensing and the degree of support available.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Some unsupported applications receive updates from community members known as "Masters of the Universe" (MOTU).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Before January 2023, community supported free software in *Universe* repository received no updates at all from Canonical Ltd.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Since 26 January 2023, customers of the Ubuntu Pro subscription service—which is free for personal use—can get Canonical-supported updates also for packages in *Universe* repository.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Free software includes software that has met the Ubuntu licensing requirements, which roughly correspond to the Debian Free Software Guidelines.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Exceptions, however, include firmware, in the Main category, because although some firmware is not allowed to be modified, its distribution is still permitted.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Non-free software is usually unsupported (Multiverse), but some exceptions (Restricted) are made for important non-free software and/or software potentially illegal in some territories.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Supported non-free software includes device drivers that can be used to run Ubuntu on some current hardware, such as binary-only graphics card drivers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The level of support in the Restricted category is more limited than that of Main, because the developers may not have access to the source code.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] It is intended that Main and Restricted should contain all software needed for a complete desktop environment.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In addition to the above, in which the software does not receive new features after an initial release, *Ubuntu Backports* is an officially recognised repository for backporting newer software from later versions of Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The *-updates* repository provides stable release updates (SRU) of Ubuntu and are generally installed through update-manager.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Each release is given its own *-updates* repository (e.g. intrepid-updates).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The repository is supported by Canonical Ltd. for packages in main and restricted, and by the community for packages in universe and multiverse.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] All updates to the repository must meet certain requirements and go through the *-proposed* repository before being made available to the public.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In addition to the *-updates* repository, the unstable *-proposed* repository contains uploads that must be confirmed before being copied into *-updates*.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] All updates must go through this process to ensure that the patch does truly fix the bug and there is no risk of regression.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Canonical previously hosted a partner repository that let vendors of proprietary software deliver their products to Ubuntu users at no cost through the same familiar tools for installing and upgrading software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The software in the partner repository was officially supported with security and other important updates by its respective vendors.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Canonical supported the packaging of the software for Ubuntu and provided guidance to vendors.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] However, in anticipation for the release of Ubuntu 22.04 LTS Canonical closed the partner repository, as the only package still hosted in it was Adobe Flash, which would not be released with 22.04.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu developer Steve Langasek said in a development mailing list that he felt the "Snap Store has matured to the point that I believe it supersedes the partner archive".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] A *Personal Package Archive* (PPA) is a software repository for uploading source packages to be built and published as an Advanced Packaging Tool (APT) repository by Canonical's Launchpad service.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] While the term is used exclusively within Ubuntu, Canonical, envisions adoption beyond the Ubuntu community.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Some third-party software that does not limit distribution is included in Ubuntu's multiverse component.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The package *ubuntu-restricted-extras* additionally contains software that may be legally restricted, including support for DVD playback, Microsoft TrueType core fonts, many common audio/video codecs, and unrar, an unarchiver for files compressed in the RAR file format.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Additionally, third-party application suites are available for download via Ubuntu Software and the Snap store, including many games such as Braid, Minecraft and Oil Rush, software for DVD playback and media codecs.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu follows a time-based release cycle, issuing new versions every six months.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Each standard release receives nine months of free support, including security updates and high-impact bug fixes.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Every fourth release, occurring in the second quarter of even-numbered years, is designated a long-term support (LTS) release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] LTS releases receive five years of free support, with the option to extend support up to ten years through the Expanded Security Maintenance (ESM) program, available through the Ubuntu Pro subscriptions, which are free for personal use.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu version numbers reflect the year and month of release.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] For example, Ubuntu 4.10 was released in October 2004.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Each release also has an alliterative code name, typically consisting of an adjective and an animal (e.g., "Bionic Beaver").
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Releases are often referred to by the adjective alone.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu releases are typically scheduled about one month after corresponding GNOME releases.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu Desktop (formally named as Ubuntu Desktop Edition, and simply called Ubuntu) is the variant officially recommended for most users.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] It is designed for desktop and laptop PCs and is officially supported by Canonical.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Variants are distinguished simply by each featuring a different desktop environment, or, in the case of Ubuntu Server, no desktop.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] LXQt and Xfce are often recommended for use with older PCs that may have less memory and processing power available.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Most Ubuntu editions and flavours simply install a different set of default packages compared to the standard Ubuntu Desktop.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Since they share the same package repositories, all of the same software is available for each of them.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu Core is the sole exception as it only has access to packages in the Snap Store.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu had some official distributions that have been discontinued, such as Gobuntu; including some previously supported by Canonical, like Ubuntu Touch, that is now maintained by volunteers (UBports Community).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Alongside the official flavours are those that are unofficial.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] These are still in the process of becoming recognised as official flavours by Canonical.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu offers Ubuntu Cloud Images which are pre-installed disk images that have been customised by Ubuntu engineering to run on cloud-platforms such as Amazon EC2, OpenStack, Microsoft Azure and LXC.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu is also prevalent on VPS platforms such as DigitalOcean.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu has support for OpenStack, with Eucalyptus to OpenStack migration tools added by Canonical.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu 11.10 added focus on OpenStack as the Ubuntu's preferred IaaS offering, though Eucalyptus is also supported.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Another major focus is Canonical Juju for provisioning, deploying, hosting, managing, and orchestrating enterprise data centre infrastructure services, by, with, and for the Ubuntu Server.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu was awarded the Reader Award for best Linux distribution at the 2005 LinuxWorld Conference and Expo in London, received favourable reviews in online and print publications, and has won InfoWorld's 2007 Bossie Award for *Best Open Source Client OS*.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In early 2008, *PC World* named Ubuntu the "best all-around Linux distribution available today", though it criticized the lack of an integrated desktop effects manager.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Chris DiBona, the program manager for open-source software at Google, said "I think Ubuntu has captured people's imaginations around the Linux desktop," and "If there is a hope for the Linux desktop, it would be them".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] As of January 2009, almost half of Google's 20,000 employees used Goobuntu, a slightly modified version of Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2012, *ZDNet* reported that Ubuntu was still Google's desktop of choice.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In March 2016, Matt Hartley picked a list of best Linux distributions for *Datamation*; he chose Ubuntu as number one.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2008, Jamie Hyneman, co-host of the American television series *MythBusters*, advocated Linux (giving the example of Ubuntu) as a solution to software bloat.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Other celebrity users of Ubuntu include science fiction writer Cory Doctorow and actor Stephen Fry.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In January 2014, the UK's authority for computer security, CESG, reported that Ubuntu 12.04 LTS was "the only operating system that passes as many as 9 out of 12 requirements without any significant risks", though it was unclear if any other Linux distributions were tested.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] As Ubuntu is distributed freely and historically, there was no registration process (still optional), Ubuntu usage can only be roughly estimated.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2015, Canonical's Ubuntu Insights page stated, "Ubuntu now has over 40 million desktop users and counting".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] W3Techs analyses the top 10 million websites only.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Wikimedia Foundation data (based on user agent) for September 2013 shows that Ubuntu generated the most page requests to Wikimedia sites, including Wikipedia, among recognizable Linux distributions.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Other supercomputers running Ubuntu also rank high on the list e.g.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] NVIDIA's Selene supercomputer still ranks highly, and was fifth-fastest one in the world in November 2022 after an upgrade from seventh place, where it entered the list in June.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Another Nvidia-based supercomputer using Ubuntu previously topped the Green500 list (it and the next one was also Ubuntu-based), a list which is a reordering of former list, ordered by power-efficiency.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] On the TOP500 list, that supercomputer was ranked 170nd (and many Ubuntu-based rank higher than that).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The public sector has also adopted Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] As of January 2009, the Ministry of Education and Science of North Macedonia deployed more than 180,000 Ubuntu-based classroom desktops, and has encouraged every student in the country to use Ubuntu-powered computer workstations; the Spanish school system has 195,000 Ubuntu desktops.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The French police, having already started using open-source software in 2005 by replacing Microsoft Office with OpenOffice.org, decided to transition to Ubuntu from Windows XP after the release of Windows Vista in 2006.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] By March 2009, the Gendarmerie Nationale had already switched 5,000 workstations to Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Based on the success of that transition, it planned to switch 15,000 more over by the end of 2009 and to have switched all 90,000 workstations over by 2015 (GendBuntu project).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Colonel Guimard announced that the move was very easy and allowed for a 70% saving on the IT budget without having to reduce its capabilities.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2011, Ubuntu 10.04 was adopted by the Indian justice system.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2004, the city of Munich, Germany, started the LiMux project, and later forked Kubuntu 10.04 LTS for use on the city's computers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] After originally planning to migrate 12,000 desktop computers to LiMux, it was announced in December 2013 that the project had completed successfully with the migration of 14,800 out of 15,500 desktop computers, but still keeping about 5,000 Windows clients for unported applications.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In February 2017 the majority coalition decided, against heavy protest from the opposition, to evaluate the migration back to Windows, after Microsoft had decided to move its company headquarters to Munich.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In May 2020, the recently elected Alliance 90/The Greens party and the Social Democrat party negotiated a new coalition agreement, stating: "Where it is technologically and financially possible, the city will emphasize open standards and free open-source licensed software".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In March 2012, the government of Iceland launched a project to get all public institutions using free and open-source software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Already, several government agencies and schools have adopted Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The government cited cost savings as a big factor for the decision, and also stated that open-source software avoids vendor lock-in.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] A 12-month project was launched to migrate the biggest public institutions in Iceland to using open-source software, and help ease the migration for others.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] US president Barack Obama's successful campaign for re-election in 2012 used Ubuntu in its IT department.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In August 2014, the city of Turin, Italy, announced its migration from Windows XP to Ubuntu for the 8,300 desktop computers used by the municipality, becoming the first city in Italy to adopt Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Starting in 2008, the Wikimedia Foundation, the non-profit organization behind Wikipedia, switched from multiple different Linux operating systems to Ubuntu (in 2019, it switched again, from Ubuntu to Debian).
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] During the 2010s, some Tesla Model S owners, discovered via little hack that the touchscreen computer for entertainment and navigation assistance, runs on an adapted version of Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In June 2019, Canonical announced that they would be deprecating support for 32-bit applications and libraries in Ubuntu 19.10.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Because Steam's Linux client depends on these 32-bit libraries, Valve announced that they would no longer be supporting Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] After uproar from the Linux gaming community, Canonical backtracked on this decision and decided to support select 32-bit libraries.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] As a result, Valve decided that Steam would support Ubuntu 19.10 again.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Wine needs most of the same 32-bit library packages that the Steam package depends on, and more, to enable its version of WoW64 to run 32-bit Windows applications.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] The parts of Wine that would continue to function without 32-bit libraries would be limited to the subset of Windows applications that have a 64-bit version, removing decades of Windows compatibility.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In Canonical's statement on bringing back the libraries, they mentioned using "container technology" in the future to make sure that Wine continues to function.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Soon after being introduced in 2012, doubts emerged on the conformance of the *shopping lens* (a feature that displays Amazon suggestions in the searching tool Unity Dash) with the European Data Protection Directive.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] A petition was later signed and delivered to Canonical demanding various modifications to the feature to clearly frame it within European law.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2013, a formal complaint on the shopping lens was filed with the Information Commissioner's Office (ICO), the UK data privacy office.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Almost one year later, the ICO ruled in favour of Canonical, considering the various improvements introduced to the feature conformed with the Data Protection Directive.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] According to European rules, this ruling is automatically effective in the entirety of the European Union.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] However, the ruling also made clear that at the time of introduction the feature was not legal, among other things, since it was missing a privacy policy statement.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu has integrated increasing quantities of advertising into the operating system's terminal, leading to multiple controversies with its user base.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2017, Canonical placed a message regarding HBO's Silicon Valley in the MOTD file, causing the message to be shown whenever a terminal session started.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Over the following years, more messages would be placed into the MOTD.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2022, ads for Ubuntu's premium service, Ubuntu Advantage, were introduced into the apt system update utility.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] This move caused controversy in the user community, with some users considering advertising a fair business model to support development, while other users found the inclusion inappropriate and annoying.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] To reach out to users who are less technical, and to foster a sense of community around the distribution, Local Communities, better known as "LoCos", have been established throughout the world.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Originally, each country had one LoCo Team.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] However, in some areas, most notably the United States and Canada, each state or province may establish a team.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] A LoCo Council approves teams based upon their efforts to aid in either the development or the promotion of Ubuntu.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu has received broad support from hardware vendors, with several manufacturers offering computers pre-installed with the operating system.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Canonical collaborates with original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) to certify and support Ubuntu on a variety of devices, primarily targeting enterprise and developer markets.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Major OEMs such as Dell, Lenovo, and HP have offered laptops and desktops with Ubuntu as an alternative to Windows, often through online configuration options or regional sales channels.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Ubuntu is also offered on the IBM Z series of mainframes.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Smaller vendors such as System76 and OnLogic also ship systems with Ubuntu pre-installed, sometimes offering firmware customization or support options through Canonical.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Many Windows applications can be run on Ubuntu, much like in other Linux distributions, using the Wine compatibility layer, which can be managed via frontends such as Bottles.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Steam has a Windows compatibility layer called Proton, and it has derivatives such as GE-Proton.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Multiple Windows virtual machines can also be installed by KVM/QEMU and Virt-Manager.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Graphics settings are easiest in QXL/SPICE mode.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] For 3D accelerated graphics performance, there is a third-party VirGL driver or GPU Full Passthrough mode.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In a networked environment, file sharing between Ubuntu Linux and Windows is possible by Samba client/server software.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Host Ubuntu Linux and the guest Windows virtual machines are also virtually networked in KVM, so file sharing between the host and virtual guest machines can also be done by the Samba in the KVM environment.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] RDP server of GNOME Remote Desktop and Remmina client software is used for remote desktop connection between Ubuntu Linux and the other OSs.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In March 2016, Microsoft announced that it would support the Ubuntu userland on top of the Windows 10 kernel by implementing the Linux system calls as a subsystem.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] At the time, it was focused on command-line tools like Bash and was aimed at software developers.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] WSL was made available with Windows 10, version 1709.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] As of 2019, other Linux distributions are also supported.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2019, Microsoft announced the new WSL 2 subsystem that includes a Linux kernel, that Canonical announced will have "full support for Ubuntu".
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] By this time, it was possible to run graphical Linux apps on Windows.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In 2021, Microsoft went on to add out-of-the-box support for graphical Linux apps, through the WSLg project.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] In May 2021, Microsoft extended its Threat and Vulnerability Management solution, which was a Windows-only solution thus far, to support Ubuntu, RHEL, and CentOS.
[src:ubuntu-linux/ubuntu] Starting with version 6, PowerShell runs on Ubuntu and can manage both Windows and Ubuntu computers remotely from either platforms.
